The problem is that my function contains logs, it is not just Taylor series=
.<div><br></div><div>For instance, I&#39;d like to =A0expand f(x,y)log(x) +=
 g(x,y) at x=3D0, y=3D0.=A0</div><div>So I expect to obtain</div><div>=A0(e=
xpansion of f(x,y)) * log(x) + expansion of g(x,y)</div>

<div><br></div><div>e.g. for one variable &quot;series&quot; does a good jo=
b</div><div><div>series(sin(x)*log(x),x=3D0)</div><div>(5) -&gt;=A0</div><d=
iv>=A0=A0 (5)</div><div>=A0=A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 log(x) =A03 =A0 log(=
x) =A05 =A0 log(x) =A07 =A0 log(x) =A09 =A0 =A0log(x) =A0 11</div>

<div>=A0=A0 =A0 log(x)x - ------ x =A0+ ------ x =A0- ------ x =A0+ ------ =
x =A0- -------- x</div><div>=A0=A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A06 =A0 =A0=
 =A0 =A0 =A0120 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A05040 =A0 =A0 =A0 362880 =A0 =A0 =A039916800<=
/div><div>=A0=A0 +=A0</div><div>=A0=A0 =A0 =A0 =A012</div><div>=A0=A0 =A0 O=
(x =A0)</div>

<div>=A0=A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 Type: GeneralUnivariatePowerSer=
ies(Expression Integer,x,0)</div></div><div><br></div><div>However this is =
not Taylor series and therefore I cannot extract coefficients as you specif=
ied.=A0</div><div>

Of course the example I have written is oversimplified. I do not know the s=
tructure of the function,=A0</div><div>it can contain sin(log(x)) for examp=
le.=A0</div><div><br></div><div>Mathematica allows repeated series expansio=
