This doesn&#39;t work, but it looks as if you want to expand sin(x+y) into =
a series in x with some &quot;strange&quot; coefficients.<div class=3D"im">=
<br>
<br>
series( =A0sin(x+y),x=3D0)<br>
<br></div>
 =A0 (1)<br>
 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0sin(y) =A02 =A0 cos(y) =A03=
 =A0 sin(y) =A04 =A0 cos(y) =A05<br>
 =A0 =A0 sin(y) + cos(y)x - ------ x =A0- ------ x =A0+ ------ x =A0+ -----=
- x<br>
 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 2 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =
6 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A024 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0120<br>
 =A0 +<br>
 =A0 =A0 =A0 sin(y) =A06 =A0 cos(y) =A07 =A0 sin(y) =A08 =A0 cos(y) =A09 =
=A0 =A0sin(y) =A010 =A0 =A0 =A011<br>
 =A0 =A0 - ------ x =A0- ------ x =A0+ ------ x =A0+ ------ x =A0- ------- =
x =A0 + O(x =A0)<br>
 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 720 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A05040 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A040320 =A0 =A0 =A036=
2880 =A0 =A0 =A03628800 <br>
 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0 =A0Type: UnivariatePuiseuxSeries(Expression(Intege=
r),x,0)<br>
<br>
and then want to expand each coefficient into a series in y.<br>
<br>
The result would then be a series in x whose coefficients are *series* in y=
. Is that what you want?<br>
<br>
Then you would go this way...<br>
<br>
TY :=3D UnivariateTaylorSeries(Fraction Integer,&#39;y,0)<br>
TX :=3D UnivariateTaylorSeries(TY,&#39;x,0)<br>
sx :=3D taylor(sin(x+y),x=3D0)<br>
coeffs :=3D [taylor(t,y=3D0)::TY for t in coefficients sx]<br>
s :=3D series(coeffs)$TX<br>
<br>
That looks a bit complicated, but can you have that in another CAS? Series =
with coefficients being series themselves? And these are no finite objects.=
 You can ask the resulting series for any coefficient you like.<br>
<br>
But I guess, you wanted something else.<br>
<br>
Ralf<br>
